## Why This Is Asked
This question probes practical design-pattern reasoning under real constraints (tenancy, rate limits, distributed cache).

## Key Concepts
- Decorator pattern for cross-cutting concerns
- Atomic Redis updates and Lua scripting
- Burst handling strategies and clock drift trade-offs
- Testing under failure and partial outages

## Code Example

```javascript
class RateLimitedService {
  constructor(next) { this.next = next; }
  async call(req){ return this.next.call(req); }
}

class RateLimiterDecorator {
  constructor(next, redis, quota, windowSec){
    this.next = next; this.redis = redis; this.quota = quota; this.windowSec = windowSec; }
  async call(req){
    const key = `rate:${req.tenant}:${Math.floor(Date.now()/this.windowSec)}`;
    const count = await this.redis.incr(key);
    if (count === 1) await this.redis.expire(key, this.windowSec);
    if (count > this.quota) throw new Error('rate limit');
    return this.next.call(req);
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test edge bursts or clock skew?
- How would you evolve to a distributed token bucket?
- How do you monitor and alert on quota breaches?
